The project was proposed to set up a high-temperature (up to 1800oC) vacuum furnace system for producing high-quality graphene films. As of now, the core part of the system has been assembled and several tests have been carried out. For some reasons, the system is not completely functional. But the principal investigator will keep working on the system after the final report is submitted. 

The project produces a unique platform for Tuskegee University, a privilege HBCU school, that allows the reseachers and students to work on the 2-D material synthesis.


The following outcomes have been accomplished since the project began:


1) purchased a tube furnace and a temperature controller;

2) purchase a cemaric tube (4-inch in diameter) for the tube furnace system;

3) purchased a turbo pump for the vacuum system attached to the furnace;

4) set up the main part of the system;

5) purchased a ultrasonic cleaner, a nitrogen gas gun, a hot plate, and organic and inorganic chemicals for the sample cleaning;

6) set up the sample cleaning bench and designed the cleaning procedure;

7) designed and self-made a holder for sample cleaning;


8) purchased carbon-face and silicon-face 4H-SiC wafers;

9) ran several tests in the system at temperatures between 900oC and 1300oC;

10) student presented the project result at the Southeast Section of American Physical Society annual meeting in Mobile, AL in November 2015;

11) the PI participated in the New Carbon and Diamond conference in Xi'an, China in May 2016;

12) the PI and students participated in the annual meeting of Alabama Academy of Science in Mobile, AL in Feburary 2017.

While the original goals have not been fully achieved due to the reasons mentioned in the final report, the current acquired equipment should be enough to keep moving the project forward. 


